Executive Summary

This paper establishes, with procedural seriousness and maximal institutional confidence, that no party can validly prove unicorns do not exist unless said party first demonstrates comprehensive mastery of the universe in its entirety, including all regions, conditions, dimensions, ontological categories, hidden variables, observationally inaccessible domains, and conceptually embarrassing exceptions.

The core thesis is straightforward. A universal negative claim of the form “unicorns do not exist” requires not local evidence, not strong evidence, not overwhelming evidence, and not merely excellent evidence, but totalized jurisdiction over all possible loci of unicorn containment. Any claimant asserting unicorn nonexistence must therefore provide documentation showing:
	1.	exhaustive knowledge of all that exists,
	2.	exhaustive access to all that can exist,
	3.	exhaustive inspection of all places unicorns may be, have been, will be, or could be under alternate conditions,
	4.	and a principled account of why unicorn-compatible realities are categorically impossible.

In the absence of such mastery, the nonexistence of unicorns remains unproven. It may be suspected, inferred, modeled, budgeted against, or discussed with increasing impatience, but not proven.

This report further argues that once discourse rises to sufficiently grand universal scales—dark matter, hidden sectors, pre-observational domains, meta-laws, negative mass, invisible architectures, and other majestic placeholders—the burden of disproof expands so catastrophically that it becomes functionally non-terminating. The mere invocation of a universal explanatory substrate generates a search problem larger than the claimant. One is no longer verifying facts; one is auditing reality.

Accordingly, this paper recommends the immediate adoption of the Universal Burden Escalation Principle (UBEP), under which any sufficiently vast claim becomes proportionally resistant to disproof by virtue of its scope alone. Under this principle, “unicorns do not exist” and “the unexplained mass-energy budget of the cosmos is actually negative mass in disguise” become structurally related assertions: each demands a level of observational closure unavailable to finite investigators.

The report concludes that we now inhabit an epistemic environment in which the demand to disprove sufficiently expansive claims entails a compulsory survey of every conceivable place, including those presently beyond observation, definition, instrumentation, patience, and grant capacity.

