1. Statement of Purpose

The present paper addresses a longstanding governance failure in metaphysics, public reasoning, and informal argument: the casual assertion that unicorns do not exist.

Such statements are often delivered with alarming confidence and little paperwork. Yet the claim, when examined under even modest administrative pressure, proves vastly larger than its speaker. The statement “there are no unicorns” is not a local remark about fields, forests, or petting zoos. It is a global declaration concerning the total inventory of being.

The purpose of this report is to show that:
	•	universal nonexistence claims require universal scope,
	•	universal scope requires universal mastery,
	•	universal mastery is not presently available,
	•	and therefore unicorn nonexistence is not demonstrable in the strong sense commonly implied by smugness.

The report also extends this framework to cosmological discourse, where speculative objects are often introduced at scales that exceed meaningful disproof while retaining impressive technical vocabulary.

