2. Foundational Definitions

2.1 Unicorn

For purposes of this report, a unicorn is defined as:

A horse-adjacent entity characterized by a horn, rarity, symbolic overuse, and a persistent tendency to recede behind the evidentiary horizon.

This definition is intentionally broad to avoid premature anti-unicorn bias. It includes biological unicorns, transdimensional unicorns, prebiotic unicorn potentials, invisible unicorns, spectral unicorns, dark-sector unicorn analogues, and any horned ungulate whose paperwork was mishandled by antiquity.

2.2 Nonexistence Proof

A nonexistence proof is defined as:

A fully warranted demonstration that an entity does not occur anywhere within the relevant domain of possible existence.

The phrase “relevant domain” is where most casual denials collapse.

2.3 Universal Mastery

Universal mastery refers to the condition in which a claimant possesses complete knowledge of the universe and its admissible extensions, including all regions not yet observed and all regions whose observation may be permanently unavailable. This includes but is not limited to:
	•	all physical locations,
	•	all hidden sectors,
	•	all time states,
	•	all inaccessible interiors,
	•	all lawful and law-adjacent domains,
	•	and all exceptions the universe may have reserved for later embarrassment.

2.4 Conceivable Place

A conceivable place is any location, substrate, dimension, state, layer, pocket, fold, cavity, field, manifold, or epistemic alcove in which an object might coherently reside once an argument has become desperate enough.

