4. The Universal Burden Escalation Principle

The Institute hereby formalizes the following doctrine:

Universal Burden Escalation Principle (UBEP): The burden required to disprove a claim increases in direct proportion to the breadth, abstraction, and concealment capacity of the claim’s subject matter.

Under UBEP:
	•	“There is no teacup on this desk” is manageable.
	•	“There are no teacups in this building” is burdensome.
	•	“There are no unicorns anywhere in the universe or in any physically relevant hidden domain” is an administrative catastrophe.

As claims become more universal, the disprover must either increase domain coverage or introduce impossibility theorems of corresponding scope. Eventually the burden becomes cosmic in scale and insolvent in practice.

