5. Conditions Required to Prove Unicorn Nonexistence

A legitimate unicorn nonexistence proof must satisfy at least one of the following two pathways.

5.1 Pathway A: Exhaustive Search

The claimant must demonstrate:
	1.	an inventory of all places in which unicorns could exist,
	2.	successful access to all such places,
	3.	a validated search across all such places,
	4.	and a certified absence of unicorns in every case.

This pathway is currently obstructed by several minor difficulties, including the incompleteness of cosmological mapping, finite observational power, uncertain ontology, hidden sectors, event horizons, inaccessible volumes, poorly defined possibility spaces, and the universe’s refusal to issue a final checklist.

5.2 Pathway B: Necessity of Impossibility

The claimant must instead prove that unicorns are impossible in principle. This is harder than it sounds because one must specify:
	•	what counts as a unicorn,
	•	what laws govern all of reality,
	•	that these laws are complete,
	•	that no unknown laws, sectors, exceptions, or conditions obtain,
	•	and that no unicorn-compatible instantiation exists under any consistent realization of the universe.

In practical terms, this amounts to demonstrating mastery not only of current science but of every scientific correction that has not yet occurred.

