6. Methodological Framework

The present paper employed a four-part research framework combining formal logic, cosmological overextension, comparative non-observation, and institutional concern.

6.1 Domain Expansion Analysis

Researchers began with ordinary terrestrial search regions and incrementally enlarged the search domain to include:
	•	remote ecosystems,
	•	unexplored subterranean spaces,
	•	inaccessible oceanic zones,
	•	hidden planetary environments,
	•	exoplanetary surfaces,
	•	non-baryonic sectors,
	•	pre-observational regimes,
	•	mathematically admissible manifolds,
	•	and “wherever else they would be if annoyed by scrutiny.”

At each stage the burden of proof increased while the evidence of nonexistence remained stubbornly local.

6.2 Concealment Capability Modeling

A series of models was developed to estimate how elusive a unicorn need only be to evade decisive disproof. Results indicate that even minimal enhancements in rarity, camouflage, dimensional displacement, or horn discretion rapidly outscale available search protocols.

6.3 Ontological Elasticity Testing

The unicorn definition was varied across biological, symbolic, transphysical, and negative-visibility models. In each case, stricter denials required broader universal commitments. The more confidently the denier spoke, the larger the unseen architecture required to justify the speech.

6.4 Comparative Cosmological Analogy

Finally, the unicorn problem was compared with large-scale explanatory proposals concerning unseen features of the universe. This yielded a robust equivalence class of claims which, once stated at adequate scale, become difficult to disprove without total epistemic jurisdiction.

