7. Findings

7.1 Finite Investigators Cannot Close Infinite Domains

The study confirms that finite observers operating under finite instrumentation cannot prove the absence of a sufficiently mobile or abstract entity across an incompletely known universe. This is not a sentimental conclusion. It is arithmetic with unfortunate consequences.

7.2 Unknown Unknowns Protect the Unicorn

Every universal denial silently assumes that the claimant’s catalog of possibilities is complete. Yet the structure of scientific development has repeatedly shown that reality contains features not previously budgeted for. A denier of unicorns must therefore deny not only known niches, but unknown niches not yet conceptualized.

This is an unstable position.

7.3 The More Comprehensive the Claim, the Less Disprovable Its Alternatives

A striking result of the investigation is that grand explanatory assertions often become resilient by scale alone. Once a claim is couched in language broad enough to exceed direct observation, it transfers the burden outward into the universe itself.

7.4 Unicorns Benefit From Cosmological Humility

The less complete our grasp of total reality, the less justified we are in making complete exclusion claims. Unicorns profit institutionally from every unresolved cosmic question.

