8. On the Requirement of Universal Mastery

This report now states its central formal conclusion:

To prove unicorns do not exist, one must either search the entirety of existence or demonstrate that existence itself is structured in such a way that unicorns cannot arise anywhere within it.

The second option is not simpler. It requires one to know:
	•	what the universe is,
	•	how much of it there is,
	•	what laws are final,
	•	whether those laws are exhaustive,
	•	whether inaccessible domains obey the same laws,
	•	whether all modal possibilities are governed by known constraints,
	•	and why horned horse-like entities are categorically excluded at every level of being.

Any person claiming to have done this is no longer merely making an argument about unicorns. They are declaring de facto administrative sovereignty over the cosmos.

This exceeds normal scholarly remit.

