9. The Cosmological Escalation Problem

9.1 From Unicorns to Universal Placeholder Entities

The argument becomes deeper, and more alarming, when applied beyond unicorns. Modern discourse frequently invokes grand unseen entities or sectors to account for unexplained phenomena. Once introduced, these entities often occupy a strange status: they are theoretically significant, observationally indirect, and rhetorically insulated by scale.

At this point, one is no longer dealing only with unicorns. One is dealing with a class of claims for which disproval requires cosmic comprehensiveness.

9.2 The Dark Matter Analogy

When large unexplained behaviors of the universe are attributed to an unseen component, the claim immediately inherits an anti-disproof shield proportional to its breadth. The unseen component may be framed as pervasive, non-luminous, indirectly inferable, and not yet directly isolated. Such framing may be scientifically useful, but its logical structure deserves attention: it is a broad invisible answer to a broad visible discrepancy.

The present paper does not deny the legitimacy of scientific modeling. It merely observes the burden geometry. Once the explanation is allowed to inhabit enormous unobserved scope, disproving alternative invisible explanations becomes correspondingly difficult.

9.3 Administrative Substitution Principle

We therefore introduce the Administrative Substitution Principle (ASP):

If a sufficiently universal unseen explanatory term is admitted into discourse, it may be replaced by another sufficiently universal unseen explanatory term unless a decisive disproof criterion unique to the substitution can be provided.

Thus, for administrative demonstration only, we may state:

The universe is not governed by dark matter; it is governed by negative mass, concealed drag, counter-gravitational resentment, or an uncooperative background fluid of epistemic density.

The moment such a statement is made at universe-scale, the burden of disproving it expands dramatically. One must now show, not merely that the claim sounds theatrical, but that every conceivable domain of relevant evidence excludes it.

The problem is structural. Grand mention creates grand burden.

