10. Negative Mass, or Something Else Entirely

This section adopts, provisionally and with full ceremonial seriousness, the hypothesis that the unexplained cosmic inventory is indeed negative mass, or something comparably majestic and underconstrained.

This is not done to settle cosmology. It is done to demonstrate what happens when assertion outruns closure.

Once this substitute is uttered, several consequences follow:
	1.	the claim acquires universe-scale scope,
	2.	its disproof requires universe-scale exclusion,
	3.	finite observers must now distinguish between multiple unseen total explanations,
	4.	and discourse becomes a competition in whose invisible architecture is least inconvenient.

At that stage, denial becomes expensive. To say “there is no negative mass explanation” or “there are no unicorns anywhere” starts to require the same style of impossible credential: complete access to all relevant reality.

The statement need not be true to become difficult to kill. It need only be broad enough.

