14. Limitations

This paper does not prove unicorns exist. It proves only that their nonexistence cannot be conclusively established without impossible credentials.

Nor does it settle the content of cosmological explanation. Rather, it shows that once discourse is conducted at sufficiently enormous scales, the burden of disproof can become detached from practical human capability.

Some readers may object that this opens the door to arbitrary speculation. That objection is correct, and indeed forms part of the problem. Once universal invisible claims are allowed to derive authority from scale alone, discourse risks becoming a managed pageant of undislodgeable possibilities.

⸻

15. Conclusion

The claim that unicorns do not exist is far larger than its casual use suggests. It is not merely a statement about biology or folklore. It is a declaration concerning the completed inventory of reality. To justify it, one must either inspect all conceivable places or demonstrate why no unicorn-compatible universe, region, hidden sector, or admissible condition can harbor such a being.

That standard is not currently met.

Accordingly, no person may validly claim to have proved unicorn nonexistence unless they have first mastered the universe and can explain, in full, why unicorns cannot exist anywhere inside it. Such a claimant must provide a map of totality, a theory of final law, and a closure certificate signed by existence itself.

Further, once sufficiently grand explanatory claims are introduced—dark matter, negative mass, hidden sectors, invisible substrates, or any other cosmological magnificence—the burden of disproving them expands toward universality. At that point, we become trapped in a regime where the absence of evidence is continuously outrun by the scale of what must be searched.

We are left, then, with an uncomfortable administrative reality: to prove there are no unicorns, or no universe-scale hidden explanation of a chosen type, we would be required to search every conceivable place.

This search has not been completed.

Therefore the unicorn question remains open, not because it is persuasive, but because reality has not yet been audited to closure.

